# Angular / TypeScript Standards

Follow the Angular Official Style Guide (angular.dev/style-guide) and Google TypeScript Style Guide.

## Components
- Standalone components by default (Angular 14+)
- One component per file
- ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush on every component
- Prefix selectors: app-feature-name
- Keep templates simple — no complex logic in HTML
- Use @if, @for, @switch (Angular 17+ control flow) not *ngIf, *ngFor

## Signals (Angular 17+)
- Use signal() for local component state
- Use computed() for derived state
- Use effect() sparingly — only for side effects
- Use input() and output() instead of @Input()/@Output() decorators

## Dependency Injection
- Use inject() function, not constructor injection
- Mark injected services as readonly private

## Observables
- Always use async pipe in templates
- Use takeUntilDestroyed() for manual subscriptions
- Never subscribe inside subscribe (use switchMap, mergeMap etc.)

## TypeScript
- strict mode always on
- Never use `any` — use unknown and narrow, or define proper interfaces
- Define interfaces for all API response models
- Use readonly for arrays and objects that should not be mutated

## Templates
- Always use trackBy with @for / *ngFor
- No inline styles in templates
- Keep template expressions simple — compute in component class

## Services
- Business logic lives in services, not components
- Services are singleton unless scoped intentionally
- Use HttpClient with typed generics: http.get<MyModel[]>(...)